# {{.ProjectName}}

A new project generated with `nucleus new`. This is an empty skeleton: a
composition root (`main.go`), configuration (`nucleus.yml`), and a place for
SQL migrations (`migrations/`). It has no application features yet — you add
those by writing **modules**.

## Run

```
go mod tidy
go run .
```

The app starts on the port in `nucleus.yml` (default `8080`). With no modules
mounted it exposes only the framework's built-in endpoints (e.g. `/healthz`,
and `/admin` for the full template).

## Add your first feature

Features live in self-contained modules that you mount in `main.go`:

```go
nucleus.New().
    FromConfigFile("nucleus.yml").
    Mount(notes.Module()).   // your module
    Start()
```

A module brings its own model, routes, and migrations. For a complete, working
example — a `notes` resource with a model, a REST `Resource` controller, and
SQL migrations — see the **`examples/mvc_api`** reference application in the
Nucleus repository and the **Quickstart** in the documentation.

## Migrations

Put SQL migrations under `migrations/` (e.g. `000001_create_notes.up.sql` /
`.down.sql`) and apply them with the CLI:

```
go run github.com/jcsvwinston/nucleus/cmd/nucleus@latest migrate --config nucleus.yml --migrations migrations up
```
